- "Capital gain" refers to the profit made from the sale of assets, such as stocks or real estate; 
- "Typical duration of education" is usually defined by the number of years required to complete a specific education level; 
- "Occupations" and their "average education years" help in understanding the relationship between education and profession; 
- "Income level" is a crucial factor in determining the capital gain and is categorized as either <=50K or >50K.

- Top three implies the highest counts of individuals for each income level; 
- Income levels are categorized (e.g., <=50K, >50K); 
- Education levels are also categorized (e.g., Bachelors, HS-grad).

- Capital gain refers to the profit from the sale of an investment or asset; 
- Capital loss refers to the loss from the sale of an investment or asset; 
- Education level is a categorical variable that can have multiple values such as Bachelors, HS-grad, etc.; 
- Income level is typically categorized into ranges such as <=50K, >50K.

sql:
SELECT education_level, duration_years
FROM education
ORDER BY duration_years DESC;
